 perspective on a notoriously neglected historical moment and challenges previous accounts of the supposed timidity of post-war culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGoth culture (Subculture)zGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)xHistory and criticism. 0aHorror tales, EnglishxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aModernism (Literature)zGreat BritainxHistory and criticism. 0aSocial changezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zGreat BritainxInfluence. 4aGothic 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh  aGothic.  aWorld War II.  aarchitecture.  acinema.  aculture.  aliterature.  aobjects.  apost-war.  atechnology.  auncanny.1 aMullen, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152613278940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526132789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526132789/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles